    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3438589417" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3438589417" />
    <a title="Edward" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/67896693-edward"><img alt="Edward" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1596383726p2/67896693.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3438589417?book_show_action=true">Jul 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Edward" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Edward" href="/user/show/67896693-edward">Edward</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780751547177" href="/book/show/11884602-the-virgin-in-the-ice">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/67896693-edward?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/67896693-edward?shelf=medieval">medieval</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3438589417" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2548078864469183125"><img src='https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1604264002i/30320906.jpg' width='400' height='230' alt='description' class='gr-hostedUserImg'/><br/><i>Sir Derek Jacobi as Brother Cadfael in the TV series</i><br/><br/>I discovered Brother Cadfael, seasoned crusader turned monk, having stumbled across (and binge-watched all of) the 1990s ITV series starring the great Sir Derek Jacobi only a few days ago. With the object of comparing the TV version with the book, I was then given a copy of the novel <i>The Virgin in the Ice</i>. However, I am going to try to steer clear of doing so in this review. Let’s just say that whoever adapted this novel for the small screen di</span>
  <span id="freeText2548078864469183125" style="display:none"><img src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/hostedimages/1604264002i/30320906.jpg" width="400" height="230" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><i>Sir Derek Jacobi as Brother Cadfael in the TV series</i><br><br>I discovered Brother Cadfael, seasoned crusader turned monk, having stumbled across (and binge-watched all of) the 1990s ITV series starring the great Sir Derek Jacobi only a few days ago. With the object of comparing the TV version with the book, I was then given a copy of the novel <i>The Virgin in the Ice</i>. However, I am going to try to steer clear of doing so in this review. Let’s just say that whoever adapted this novel for the small screen did a splendid job.<br><br><i>It was early in November of 1139 that the tide of civil war, lately so sluggish and inactive, rose suddenly to sweep over the city of Worcester</i>. With these impressive and atmospheric words begins <i>The Virgin in the Ice</i>, the sixth instalment in the chronicles of Brother Cadfael. It is set during the Anarchy, the civil war between King Stephen and Empress Maud (which, incidentally, forms the historical backdrop to Ken Follett’s very engaging though perhaps not as poetic novel <i>The Pillars of the Earth</i>). Following this attack on Worcester, two noble children and a Benedictine nun flee, intending to make their way to Shrewsbury, but they never arrive. It falls to Brother Cadfael and Hugh Beringar, the Deputy Sheriff, to locate this missing company of three.<br><br>The beauty of Peters’ prose is certainly not limited to the novel’s opening sentence. Surprisingly but quite wonderfully, Cadfael recollects his youth in Antioch, whose sultry, bustling streets are depicted beguilingly and contrast with the harsh, cold winter of England. This unexpected evocation of Antioch was most welcome, and I would have loved more of this. Alas, this was not to be; thereafter, the novel remains very much in snowy Shropshire. That isn’t to say that the perilous world of medieval England, with its outlaws and its lethal climate, is not also brought beautifully to life. Peters is an elegant writer (although I did take exception to one aspect of her writing, which I discuss below) and her prose is solid throughout.<br><br>The <i>Cadfael Chronicles</i> are credited with popularizing the genre of historical mystery (to which one of my favourite books <i>
  <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3102373869" rel="nofollow noopener">The Name of the Rose</a>
</i>belongs) and it is easy to see why: <i>The Virgin in the Ice</i> was easy to read with a plot of pleasing intricacy.<br><br>Unfortunately, there ends my praise for the book. <br><br>My main problem with it was that the plot seemed unbalanced. Indeed, I even grew rather frustrated around the page 150 mark. Up to this point, the action moved along swiftly enough with Cadfael and Beringar discovering various clues, but when the novel reached its climax, it seemed to last for about 100 pages. Not only was this excessively drawn out, but during that time, the same irksome plot point occurred twice. This part of the book could have done with some serious pruning and I really think it would have been improved were it 50 pages shorter.<br><br>As much as I liked Peters’ poetic prose (and I really did rate her as a fine writer), her metaphors were far too forced for my taste. Perhaps some readers would call them lyrical; I would call them clumsy. Here is one at which I took particular umbrage: ‘twenty voices at least plaited a lattice of noise through the haze’. This did not help me to imagine the sound of those voices better. If anything it made me think of potato lattices. These awkward analogies, and there were many, felt out of place and at times obfuscated the narrative. <br><br>To round off, then. I really enjoyed the first 150 pages of <i>The Virgin in the Ice</i>. After that, I struggled. I wouldn’t recommend this book if you have seen the TV version, which trimmed the story to much more pleasing proportions. Perhaps if I had read one of the Cadfael books not adapted for TV, I would be writing a much more praising review. Somehow, though, I can’t help thinking that the problems I had with this novel are features of Peters’ writing and not particular to this story.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2548078864469183125" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


