<div id="review_2978050370" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2978050370" />
    <a title="Jeanne" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7743315-jeanne"><img alt="Jeanne" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609344390p2/7743315.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2978050370?book_show_action=true">Sep 15, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jeanne" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jeanne" href="/user/show/7743315-jeanne">Jeanne</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/22856058-the-virgin-in-the-ice">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7743315-jeanne?shelf=read-2019">read-2019</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7743315-jeanne?shelf=read-around-the-world">read-around-the-world</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7743315-jeanne?shelf=read-women">read-women</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7743315-jeanne?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/7743315-jeanne?shelf=mysteries">mysteries</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2978050370" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12616308265532504872"><em>“Never go looking for disaster... Expect the best, and walk so discreetly as to invite it, and then leave all to God.”</em> (Kindle 1613)<br/><br/><em>The Virgin in the Ice</em> is the 6th book in the Brother Cadfael series. This is an unusual book in the Brother Cadfael series as the mystery is often part of an ordinary, but observant life. In <em>The Virgin in the Ice</em>, there is more death and mayhem than typical for this series. As a woman living in the 21st century, however, I am often surprised by how few deaths take p</span>
  <span id="freeText12616308265532504872" style="display:none"><em>“Never go looking for disaster... Expect the best, and walk so discreetly as to invite it, and then leave all to God.”</em> (Kindle 1613)<br /><br /><em>The Virgin in the Ice</em> is the 6th book in the Brother Cadfael series. This is an unusual book in the Brother Cadfael series as the mystery is often part of an ordinary, but observant life. In <em>The Virgin in the Ice</em>, there is more death and mayhem than typical for this series. As a woman living in the 21st century, however, I am often surprised by how few deaths take place in the Brother Cadfael mysteries, set in the middle of a civil war. (In this one, it is late 1139 and Empress Maud and King Stephen are fighting locally.) As Brother Cadfael observed, occasional mayhem is not surprising: <em>"In a land at war with itself, ...you may take it as certain that order breaks down, and savagery breaks out”</em> (Kindle 50).<br /><br />This is also an unusual book in that it is a comedy of errors (if comedy and wartime can go together). It is almost as though Brother Cadfael is carrying a dozen balls: every time he picks one up and believes he has solved the problem set for him, another drops, although not of his doing. Another metaphor, perhaps more apt: Remember those toys you played with as a child, with magnets in their base? Attempt to bring them together with the wrong poles aligned, and they fly apart. There was much "flying" here.<br /><br />Like the other Brother Cadfaels, <em>The Virgin in the Ice</em> is peopled by extraordinary characters: Cadfael, Hugh Beringer, and his wife Aline being three of these. They are observant, honorable, competent, socially skilled, beautiful, and hardworking. Not all of Peters' characters are extraordinary, but an unusual proportion are like 13-year-old Yves, who likely could leap tall buildings in a single bound. This is the first appearance of the truly extraordinary Oliver de Bretagne, who awes Yves and his sister, and stands out in this otherwise unusual group despite having only a bit part. <br /><br />Like many Brother Cadfael mysteries, the central characters have strong moral cores: <em>“Don’t arrogate to yourself God’s own role of apportioning blame and praise, even when the blame lands on your own shoulders. That's a kind of arrogance, too”</em> (Kindle 1390). Nonetheless, this is 12th century England and the moral conclusions are often different from what one might expect. Cadfael observed, <em>It would have been an insult to repent of having loved a woman like Mariam</em> (Kindle 223).<br /><br />I remain a big fan of Ellis Peters and Brother Cadfael. The books in this series are comfort food: competence exists, people are moral and honorable, and happy(ish) endings are possible, even in the midst of deeply horrible events. Luckily, there are many installments in this series.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12616308265532504872" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

